Headlines.Headline: Hospira Swings to Third-Quarter Profit on Gains, Improved Sales

PARAGRAPH.#text: Hospira Inc. HSP swung to a third-quarter profit, partly due to fewer charges, as the medical-device maker's sales improved more than expected. The maker of injectable drugs and infusion technologies has seen its bottom line hampered by heavy costs to resolve regulatory concerns over manufacturing at some of its plants, a burden which has also hurt revenue growth of late. In an effort to lower costs and support the supply of key antibiotic products, Hospira agreed in August to pay about $200 million to acquire a manufacturing plant and a related research-and-development facility from the India-based drug maker Orchid Chemicals & Pharmaceuticals Ltd.

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Critics of Univision's proposed $3
billion takeover of Hispanic Broadcasting Corp. say the amount of control
it has over Latino performers could thwart competition in the U.S.
Spanish-language media market.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Univision Keeps Short Leash on Stars
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Eduardo Porter
Headlines.Headline: Telemundo Opposes Univision Deal

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Telemundo voiced opposition to the
pending merger of Univision and Hispanic Broadcasting.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Telemundo Opposes Univision Deal
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Michael Allen
Headlines.Headline: Televisa Chief Weighs U.S. Citizenship

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Emilio Azcarraga Jean, head of
Mexican entertainment company Grupo Televisa, is considering becoming a
U.S. citizen in order to pursue a possible business combination with
Univision Communications.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Televisa Chief Weighs U.S. Citizenship
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: FCC Poised to Approve Univision Deal

The FCC is close to approving
Univision's acquisition of Hispanic Broadcasting. Opponents are lobbying
hard to block the deal.

Broadcasting faces mounting opposition from Democrats.

Department for its takeover of Hispanic Broadcasting.

antitrust lawsuit by Spanish Broadcasting against rival Spanish-language
radio group Hispanic Broadcasting and Clear Channel Communications.

Headlines.Headline: Shares Climb in Tech-Led Rally

Share prices rallied, with technology
and telecommunications stocks leading the way, and a bullish stock market
recommendation from Lehman Brothers adding steam.

Headlines.Author: Yochi J. Dreazen
Headlines.Headline: Univision Gets Tentative Approval

PARAGRAPH.#text:
The Justice Department has
tentatively approved Univision's acquisition of Hispanic Broadcasting, a
deal that would create a Spanish-language radio and television
powerhouse.

Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Eduardo Porter
Headlines.Headline: Spanish-Radio Firms Blast Arbitron

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Arbitron is facing a blistering
attack from the four largest Spanish-language radio broadcasters in the
U.S., who contend the ratings company is dragging its feet in changing its
measurement techniques to count their listeners.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Spanish-Radio Firms Blast Arbitron
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Eduardo Porter
Headlines.Headline: Arbitron to Revamp Samples

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Arbitron agreed to weight its
Hispanic audience samples by language preference, bowing to demands of
Spanish-language radio broadcasters who have complained that their market
clout is being underestimated.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Arbitron to Revamp Samples
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Eduardo Porter
Headlines.Headline: Hispanic Radio Feud Boils Over

PARAGRAPH.#text:
The long-running brawl between the
top two Spanish-language radio companies has involved lawsuits and outright
insults. But with the boom in Spanish-language media, this noisy sideshow
has moved to the industry's center ring.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Hispanic Radio Feud Boils Over
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Robert O'Brien
Headlines.Headline: Telecom Sector Boosts Market

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Blue-chip stocks posted their first
gain since Monday of last week with shares of telecommunications-service
and -equipment providers giving the market a much-needed boost.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Telecom Sector Boosts Market
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Joel Millman
Headlines.Headline: 'Ay, Preciosa': Spanish Oldies Thrive

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Spanish-language oldies have found a
niche in America, thanks to an immigrant community that keeps on growing,
and graying -- and cares little for current Latino crossover superstars
such as Shakira and Enrique Iglesias.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: 'Ay, Preciosa': Spanish Oldies Thrive
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Robert O'Brien
Headlines.Headline: Industrials Gain Big, Again

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Wall Street continued to show some
success in getting investors to focus on its efforts to rehabilitate its
shaken image rather than on some admittedly spotty fundamentals. allowing
blue chips to rise.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Industrials Gain Big, Again
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: Rival Sues to Block Univision Merger

Spanish Broadcasting filed an
antitrust suit against Hispanic Broadcasting, in a bid to scuttle its $3.5
billion deal with Univision.

Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: By Eduardo Porter
Headlines.Headline: Univision to Buy Radio Group

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Univision agreed to buy Hispanic
Broadcasting for about $3.5 billion in stock, in a deal that would join the
U.S.'s biggest Spanish-language TV and radio groups.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Univision to Buy Radio Group
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Joel Millman
Headlines.Headline: Arbitron Rides Radio Into Mexico

PARAGRAPH.#text:
In a push for expansion, top ratings
analyst for U.S. radio markets Arbitron has begun syndicating statistics
for Mexican stations. The efforts are a gradual build-up of service to
Latin America that will soon include market-share data for Guadalajara and
Monterrey.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Arbitron Rides Radio Into Mexico
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: Clear Channel Profits Fall on Charge

Clear Channel posted a $16.7 billion
loss due to an accounting change, but its results indicated a recovery in
radio advertising.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Clear Channel Profits Fall on Charge
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: Seven Questions: Janus Orion's Ron Sachs

PARAGRAPH.#text:
The Janus Orion fund's 2% loss over
the past 12 months -- less than most of its cratered peers -- highlights
the blue period for most funds. Portfolio manager Ron Sachs says he hasn't
changed his style, but isn't about to hop on the tech tiger again.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Seven Questions: Janus Orion's Ron Sachs
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

shares of several companies, including Lennar, GE, Best Buy and Pfizer.

Modest Increase

as better-than-expected earnings from Hewlett Packard and optimism about an
economic recovery rallied shares.

U.S. Stocks Post
Modest Increase

Home Depot, Whirlpool Fall
On Another Day of Big Losses

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Consumer-products and retail shares
took the brunt of a broad selloff, as the worst consumer confidence numbers
in seven years spooked investors already soured on the prospects for the
economy's recovery.

On Another Day of Big Losses

billion.

familiar with the situation said.

interested in buying Telemundo, the Spanish-language television
company.

Techs up on Upbeat Talk
From Intel Chief Executive

executive boosted the company's stock, as well as the whole semiconductor
sector, helping market averages. The Nasdaq closed higher, up 19.00, or
0.92%, at 2087.38, and the Dow finished up just 41.17 points, or 0.39%, to
10551.18.

Techs up on Upbeat Talk
From Intel Chief Executive

High Techs Lift Nasdaq,
But Blue Chips End Lower

Technology issues
 ended the month on
a bright note, but some economically sensitive blue-chip names couldn't
sustain their recent strength, leaving market averages mixed on the
day.

But Blue Chips End Lower
